    public class ValueFactoryParser<V,C extends V,ABT,A extends C,JBT,J extends C,B extends V,M extends V,N extends V,S extends V>
extends Object
implements Parser<V,C,ABT,A,JBT,J,B,M,N,S>
    Concrete implementation of Parser.

    Concurrency

    Each instance of ValueFactoryParser stores references to a ValueFactory, a set of JsonUrlOptions, and JsonUrlLimits. The state of each call to the Parser.parse(CharSequence) method (or one of its variants) is local. That means it is technically safe to reuse a ValueFactoryParser across multiple threads. However, the parser does provide access to its set of options(), via a reference to a mutable set. That means that it's possible to change the set by doing something like: 

    JsonUrlParser p = ...;
p.options().add(JsonUrlOption.SKIP_NULLS);
    Therefore, reusing a ValueFactoryParser is not recommended. Because this object it so lightweight, and you're unlikely to realize any real world benefit, you're better off simply creating a new instance each time you need one.
    Since:
    2019-09-01
    Author:
    jsonurl.org, David MacCormack
